Review_Content:
﻿D∆WN - Infrared 


Post-Blackheart I have high expectations for any Dawn Richard release but they aren’t met here; especially surprising given this is produced by Kingdom whose production is too bloated for her style. Gone is Dawn’s clever lyricism from Blackheart which was at times abstract, metaphorical and personal. Infrared is thematically promising but never really goes anywhere.

﻿I have major respect for chaz's diverse and prolific output, he's always pushing himself in a new direction. The few things I've actively listened to in the past haven't held me but I like this album: hip, poppy electro with a loner vibe.

Review_Content: ï»¿A varied album of what I think of as adult contemporary. The use of a drum machine on some tracks I thought hampered the preciousness and authenticity that hangs around the rest of the album. Consistent with the rest of their catalog there are standout pop tracks with beautiful lyrics to be found but I prefer other albums of theirs.

ï»¿Talented dude: natural knack for songwriting and I love the production. The lyrical content needs work, felt juvenile (or am I just getting old? I accept that) and the radio concept could've used refining; felt like filler. 


I plan to revisit this further and keep an eye on his future, looks bright.

ï»¿Great record. 


I've been a big fan of Nicolas jaar since his BBC Essential mix (I'll express my appreciation for the essential mix in a separate post but I found it life changing (seriously)). At the time his other mixes were distinctly different and catered more to the dance floor. The tracks on these mixes seemed to be little more than a tasteful vocal sample, after laughter comes tears for example, with bass and rhythm mixed in. Another element I've appreciated of his is the slightly off-tempo drum lines which add a human element to the music. 


Since then his proper releases have shown similarities but the songs are more polished and structured. On 2012-2017 it seems he's returning to the basic sample approach and aiming clearly at the dance floor, the result is seriously good and the release I wasn't sure he'd make. 


I view this album as 'uncut' where most tracks could easily be edited down, truthfully I think he could've worked this into a perfect 25-30 minute mix. But what's here is so good that I think it's a must hear for any dance fan and an accessible release I expect will be picked up by a lot of DJs.
ï»¿This is music for idiots
ï»¿amazinggggggg drunk piano rock for poets
ï»¿Everything uptown part 1 is prototypical brainfeeder: Spacey hazy LA future electro. The later 2/3s has it's moments but gets repetitive, causing the album to feel bloated overall.

﻿An excellent representation of 70s rock. It's a straightforward pop record but Rundgren does a number of styles well. It has a pleasant, rich, easy-going feel with lots of lovely elements: catchy numbers, harmonies, solos. Reminds me of soft radio rock and bands like Queen, The Beach Boys as well as Zeppelin's tender tracks. His natural songwriting ability and multi-instrumentation talent make this something original that rewards repeat listenings. 


Recommended, I've explored a bit of his catalog but keep coming back here.
Tags: Power Pop , Pop Rock , Prog Rock, Rock

﻿Memorable pop blending elements of punk, funk and a certain reggae vibe; kinda like The Clash doing sophisti-pop. This is my favorite Style Council album as it's focused pure pop goodness and not weighed down by medicore explorations into styles they don’t do so well.
Tags: Pop Rock , Mod , Soul, Electronic , Jazz , Rock

Review_Content: ﻿Another quality release from XL: Big bass heavy electro for the kids, total fun. I know nothing about the artist but it's my favorite EP of his on Spotify.

﻿A solid album by a friend of a friends band with some of the best original music I've heard by people I know. There's never a dull moment due to the albums liveliness and variety of instrumentation, it feels like there is a new sound every 4 bars. The biggest compliment I'll give is the range of influences they successfully draw from. 


The Holladays are talented songwriters that know what's up, I would be really interested to hear more from these guys.
﻿Epic, relentless, bluesy metal; this shit kicks ass.

﻿I liked a bunch of the tracks: 


* A little max (parfait) 
* Switchblade, 
* Backward country boy blues 
* Caravan 
* Money jungle 


I found the rest a little too boppy or slow. The level of musicianship is extraordinary and I especially love Mingus on bass who adds an element that's not usually found in small group jazz.
﻿Like a weirder Animal Collective, I dig it.

﻿I was very excited for this record given the timberland / neptunes production. The first three tracks: filthy, midnight summer jam, and sauce are excellent and Timberlake is in vintage form channeling jamiroquai at times. Lyrically things seem more personal and creative which I appreciate. Midnight summer jam is especially good, I can just imagine that harmonica being the perfect thing to cut the atmosphere in a late night sweaty club. 


The rest of the album really doesn't hold me, just kinda not very good and I don't subscribe to the 'man of the woods' message. It's strange given the amount of talent that was involved.

﻿The core string of tracks that sample classic funk, starting with Morris day n' night, is engaging and varied; well suites to hip hop instrumental fans that like funk. Unfortunately the album takes frequent detours into other ideas that aren't as strong. A funk focused ep would've been great.

﻿A precious ambient-electro album with a careful ebb and flow. Maintains a cozy sick-day from work feel and houses a few blissful vocal-pop moments sprinkled throughout. 


He is a talented songwriter and I look forward to checking out more of his catalog, I'm surprised he's not more popular.

﻿So much ink has been spilled about the Smiths I won't even mention their sound. I've found their records inconsistent but this is a good listen all the way through and contains some of their best tracks. 


Highly accessible and an excellent starting place if you've never heard them, recommended.

﻿Revisiting this since it first came out almost 10 years ago and it's no surprise this band had it's break out. The album keeps a good groove throughout, woven together with interesting electronic textures. I particularly love the first half of opal magic, I've listened to it dozens of times and still think it's a great song. Thematically the lyrics are a little dramatic but it feels like a natural part of his singing style and not pretentious. Recommended.

﻿This is a combined review for Arla ep’s I, II and III which I think taken together make a great album. I'm not very good at classifying electronic music but this is quality UK electro like Jamie xx and Four Tet. Each of the EP’s compliments each other, wirth EP II incorporating manipulated vocal hooks as part of the production. 


On another note, I really need to check out more releases by XL. Starting to see them as an emblem of quality.

﻿Daedelus is such an extraordinary talent that all of his catalog is worth a listen. I'm not always in the mood for his rapid fire production style but when I am I find there's always something interesting to hear. Good tracks on days demise include viva vida and sama legrand.

﻿Suggested by a friend for pre-kaputt destroyer, this fell flat on my ears. Lacks chemistry and seemed pretentious, not surprising coming from these drama queens. 


Bejar's lyrics are good, album highlights are tracks where he's singing.

﻿This chick’s real talented and has a refreshing style with an approachable persona, not trying to play a part. This album houses a well-executed vision that I could see people loving but I found it a little uneven. Definitely some standout tracks (especially chrome) make her someone to watch.

﻿I really like this band and support their style of punk, owing a lot to 80s influences like the replacements and feelies. Lyrically it has a well-read feel that I find is missing with today's lyricists. 


I can see spending more time with this album and liking it more in time, definitely a band I'd like to see live.
﻿OK but falls short of their early catalog.
﻿I like his style but the use of strings watered down the funk.

﻿Overall it's a nice set of pop songs that are varied in their songwriting. Rubblebucket is a big group with layers of instrumentation including brass and keys. Kalmia Traver’s voice is pleasant, reminds me of Lætitia Sadier from Stereolab (though missing the lyrical genius there). Happiness is abuzz on Omega LaLa with an almost skalike energy. I think the version on Spotify has some distracting sound effects mixed in as it seems different than the version I used to listen to, small slight though. 


I listened to this record a lot when it first came out and it doesn't feel as strong upon revisiting. On a personal level it reminds me of a person I don't speak with, maybe's what makes this a strange album to hear again.

﻿American Trailer is a guitar driven jazz album with a heavy blues lean. Songs incorporate a variety of jazz styles that includes Beatles covers. I generally like the bluesier tracks better (episode one, Danube Delta blues, song for Jimi) but the slower ballad-like pieces are good too, almost like a lively Jim Hall. 


I found this album while looking for albums that feature the fantastic drummer Rudy Royston. I'm glad I did as American Trailer has introduced me to Rudy Linka whose guitar playing I really enjoy here: sweet tone that's precise but laid-back at the same time. 


American Trailer is an accessible album with pop-like melodies and familiar blues licks that I recommend.
﻿Not bad just boring, far cry from their early catalog.

Review_Content:
﻿I approached this album as if it were a Four Tet side project but he's not the focus here. Instead it's a highly accessible album of superbly written, tight post-rock. The drums are way up in the mix and I like that aspect of rhythm here. Jeffers is a good drummer, nothing revolutionary but he's got a playful approach and switches up the lines constantly. It's relatively bare bones otherwise which is surprising considering four tets knack for layering. 


An enjoyable listen for fans of post rock or an excellent starting place for those unfamiliar with the genre.

﻿I'm not a huge ambient fan so it feels wrong reviewing a career spanning collection for an artist I'm not familiar with (as opposed to a curated best-of). Still I enjoyed the tracks with vocal loops like Un Hombre Oscuro and Sue Que Estas Ahi, as well as a very pretty The Ten Heads of Someone and proto-vaporwave Suelo Para Pisar. There are a number of new-agey tracks haven't aged as well. 


I can only ever promote documents like this that breathe new life into forgotten artists. Music from memory has an interesting outlet I'll continue to explore.

﻿Light, floating electronic music heavily influenced by ambient; an excellent example of how genres continue to evolve and influence each other. The album unfolds in an almost take-off like fashion where earlier tracks utilize a drum machine and feature a focused groove, almost Air like at times. The album gradually transitions into something much spacier and open that reminded me of solo David Gilmour, I enjoyed the stretched out guitar playing here. 


Gonna check out more by them.
﻿It's an OK collection but not worth seeking out in my opinion. I prefer tracks by the individual artists to what was located here in some cases ie Yusef Lateef.

﻿What’s it sound like? 
Difficult to describe, I guess I'd call this experimental new wave jazz; compositionally close to modern classical. 


Thoughts 
It's best to approach this with an open mind as it's not really like anything else I've heard before. The album incorporates a number electro, pop, marimba, world, and dub moments and combines them into an engaging and exciting listen. I can see this album aging well as it rewards repeat listens with its layers and subtleties, even on my first few listens I found myself finding new things. 


To me this is what the avant garde should be: exploring new ideas through familiar approaches.

This is pop-rock songwriting at it's finest, refined in a radio friendly way but with a style that's distinctly there's. Thomas Mars is a fantastic frontman and I love his lyrics, kinda cryptic at times but he sings with an understanding of life that's hard not to find part of your own self or experiences in. 


I've got to thank Cyril for turning me on to these guys, probably my favorite French export after Daft Punk.

﻿What’s it sound like? 


Folksy 60s new York singer songwriter with dramatic string arrangements. No bass or percussion, Nico's distinct voice is at the center of it all, singing lyrics about friends, life, change, stories of new york (especially convincing considering she didn't write any of the lyrics). 


I like the dark textures of ‘it was a pleasure then’, an electric guitar is employed to do general noodling and effects before breaking into some dissonant soundscape. It's particularly effective given the album had been entirely acoustic. 


Thoughts 


This album has aged very well. Nico's nonchalant character feels very New York and the album carries a feeling of walking around the city. Her vocal range is limited but her distinct masculinity is appealing. 


I see this continuing to have a 'cool' appeal for future listeners through her association with the velvet underground. My only previous exposure to Nico was on the VU's debut, surprised to know a number of the singles.

This is great. I don't see the album having any lasting replayability but in 2018 it works. Feels like it's a continued progression of the 'not really saying anything' lyricism but proves that content isn't needed if it's catchy. With that in mind this is a true reflection of the times and communication: the message doesn't matter as long as it looks or sounds a certain way. He's also got some impressive guest spots who adapt to his style and flow. I find this telling about his relevance as he's pulling big names into his orbit. 


I think the mistake someone could make is approaching this as a traditional rap album. His style is so drastically different than say illmatic that we need to see it as a purely aesthetic piece and consider it differently. In that way it succeeds massively. Creating something original that's just throwing constant rhythmic hooks at you. It's almost as if you're listening to a warm-up session where they're just feeling out the beat trying to flow, not working on the perfect verse. I see a lot of followers from this. He's actually at his worse in the middle of the album when he's speaking clearly.

Release_Title: A Rift In Decorum (Live At The Village Vanguard)
Review_Content:
﻿Sounds like? 
Modern jazz that is rooted in tradition but veers into tasteful experimental deconstructions. 






Moods 
Downtown jazz 






Thoughts 
Impressive stuff, wholeheartedly suggest this to fans of modern jazz. 


I need to look up the style this is called but I feel this is part of a broader move forward for jazz. His compositions follow a general pattern with a somber melodic start to these songs that veers into intense free jazz like breakdowns. They illustrate a masterful knowledge of post-bop and mindful control on limits free jazz breakdowns. 


I think what sets this apart (ie from Justin Brown's latest) is the way the band keeps it together and doesn't totally abandon a collective playing. Jazz, as a genre, evolved into something where people seemed to go free, fusion or forced to play as a revivalist. This record combines something of the free and revitalist approach but does so in a modern way that feels fresh. 


Credit is due to the band and leadership of Ambrose. He's a trumpet player who's style I actually enjoy and is executing a vision perfectly. Justin Brown's drumming is always impressive and his influence can't be understated. I find he works very well as a member as a band rather than a leader; see my notes on nyeusi for more there. 


Conflicted on what to rate this so gave it a 3 for now. Believe I need a bit more time to really set in with listening sessions where I can enjoy this. Overall a great record with fresh ideas, recommended.

Thoughts 
I love Muhammad's drumming which gives this an incredibly quick backbeat that only a true master can provide. Add in some punchy bass and solos that carry with energy and character, has a 70s grit to it. 


The writing is great too, taking pop and turning them into jazz songs (really well done, not just half-baked covers) Sudan is a great piece where I feel the band gels more and feels slightly less arranged. (Admittedly the track I said to myself ok this is a really good album). I don't want you know more is a greater closer. Bit new Orleans brass with a floating keys line and funky get up and dance drum beat, ends with the right energy. 


Allmusic got it right: 


But the complete disregard for the political correctness of "Jazz" itself, in order to get the deeply funky and soulful grooves across, is what makes this set so damn special and even spiritual in its inspiration. Jazz purists lost all credibility when they slagged this one off, caught as they were in tainted, even racist views of the past that made no allowances for jazz musicians to actually follow their time-honored tradition of mining the pop music of the day to extend the breadth and reach of jazz itself. Anybody who wants to believe that George Gershwin is somehow more important than George Porter Jr. is already lost in his own cultural fascism. Muhammad, who understands this better than anyone, pulled out all the stops here and blasted out one amazingly tough, funky slab. Brilliant.

I don't know why, call it a natural curiosity, but growing-up I loved the radio and would spend hours taking in anything I could hear. I find pleasure discovering sounds and appreciate art that maintains this same dynamism. It's reflected in a broader cultural awareness with my generation, whose been raised with the internet and the power of having humanity's entire cultural output instantly available. So what do you do with it? You take your favorite parts and begin creating something new, sampling in other words. 


I find this to be a representative album for today's sample based culture as Banks, a versatile MC, floats effortlessly between pop and rap on this impressive set of alt-electro productions (think sampling today rather than the past). ﻿Sounds like? 
Rock and Jazz fusion 






Moods 
Groovin - the perfect miles record for rock fans 






Thoughts 
Perhaps the most 'rock’ record in the miles discography. Purists might disagree but I think this is an exemplar of rock and jazz fusion due to it's heavy rock lean and accessibility. The mixing is weird: no single tracks but rather two lengthy sides where thing's fade into the other, often forcing unfinished ideas to come together abruptly; almost like an impatient DJ. Anyhow the music: 


Side 1 is the better example of the miles 'rock’ thing with a driving bass line and angular guitars propelling things forward. It’s an extended classic 70s rock jam with a groove. 


Side 2 is where thing's get a bit more chilled out and experimental. The music wanders and isn't as focused. Still.. things are being worked out and it's fantastic music by any means. A highlight is the moment ‘in a silent way’ breaks through. Glorious! 


I consider miles electric period one of the pinnacles of music and this is one of the best intros, especially for non-jazz fans. 


Essential music.

﻿Sounds like? 
Prince singing while playing the piano 




Moods 
An intimate session with the purple one 






Thoughts 
An interesting artifact that I think all Prince fans should hear once. Here we have a sketchbook like view of Prince's songwriting process (Purple rain, for instance, is just a brief thought in this session. It would be fleshed out months later). Intimacy is immediately established given the stripped down nature of this recording: gone are the sequenced to perfection drum machines and synths that would obscure him at times. It's as if you're hearing him with his guard is down and the beauty of his songwriting takes center stage. 


While Prince's multi instrumentation ability is common knowledge here we learn he's a fantastic piano player, effortlessly toying with melody. 


I see, feel and understand his soulful approach to music better after listening to this. Not because of the final product but the heart that goes into it. 


Essential listening and gem in his esteemed catalog.

Thoughts 
It took awhile for me to recognize the genius here. I think I was too young when I first heard it, I wasn't drawn to it's sound. Even now I wouldn't recommend this to anyone under 30, the essence is lost without that unnerving only adulthood can provide. 


At surface level it's boring adult pop, listen a little closer and you'll hear solid American folk songs. Backed by light (mostly) and tight instrumentation, it's just the right amount of precise while not feeling overly polished; a quality which typically bothers me but here it fits. Tweedy's got a pleasant voice and is an exceptional lyricist, switching between abstract thoughts and relatable lyrics on love. Few writers can capture anxiety, in its many forms, so poetically. It's his ability that elevates this album, turning these dense subjects into carthic singalongs. Ultimately the listener is left with a feeling of hope through the reliability in his words. True art captures some element of the human condition and I think Wilco nailed it on Yankee hotel foxtrot 


Anyone who's ever experienced that spinning out of control feeling will understand the value of something grounded. The perfect soundtrack for something as enjoyable as a pleasant autumn day or as heavy as your car ride after checking out of the insane asylum.

'34 klezma' begins with a yiddish rhythm and rich strings and piano, it's decadent in a classical sense.

﻿Sounds like? 
Gritty hip electro house 


Moods 
Raw textures compliment strong productions on this hip minimal electro ep 






Thoughts 
Resident Advisor said it well: 


Sine Language features four very different productions, putting K-Lone's versatility on display. The title track draws on a vintage Detroit style, mixing electro beats and hip-hop vocals—hardly a novel idea in 2019. But a sweet, subtly out-of-place ambient breakdown interrupts the flow at the perfect moment, keeping things interesting. "Batacuda" and "Bells" are experiments at slower tempos, something we've seen a lot of from UK-based producers in recent years, particularly those in the Timedance camp. "Batacuda" floats along, emanating a drowsy humidity, while "Bells" is moody and thoughtful, coated in a chiming haze. "Missed Calls," a carefully crafted piece of taught, polyrhythmic braindance, is probably the best track on the EP. With this kind of eclecticism, a producer takes the risk of spreading themselves too thinly, but not K-Lone. He brings an intelligence and inventiveness to everything he does, unifying his work and making it essential listening every time.

Moods 
Vince Staples best? Rap that incorporates the interesting parts of electro 






Thoughts 
I admire hybrids where artists take sounds from a genre's fringes and incorporate them into a popular format. Kanye gets a lot of credit for that with Yeezus but I like this better. Production is what makes Big Fish such a worthwhile record with Staples leveraging a variety of electro producers to create a quilt that is intense, booming and always engaging. His rhymes are direct in delivery, creating a steady presence and interesting juxtaposition against the variety. 


The result is a great modern Rap record with a youthful but wise energy. It's uneven but one that's bursting with provoking ideas on what makes effective music. I prefer that to the world of over polished pop without soul and have rewarded it with reslistens.

it's a solid record overall. Bit 'one note' as far as songwriting goes, general pop rock fare. Songs are high energy, rousing and stomping. Lyrically he sings in a highly personal manner with details of relatable memories about failed relationships, getting drunk, and general adulthood confusion. 


Sound like a lot of albums? I'd say where this delivers is on the genuineness of those moments and that it sounds exactly like a good night out on the Lower East Side of Manhattan feels: an exciting energy powered only by the moment. 


It's fun if you live that or, if you're like me, a bit removed relive those memories for a bit. I imagine this band would be fantastic live.

﻿Sounds like? 
The music is an Americana blend of blues, country, gospel, and folk rock elements. This music is characterized by the purposeful use of simplified sounds to reflect the then-current vogue of blues and other roots music being used in many roots rock bands. Wray's guitar-work, composing, and vocals reflected modern rock influences. 






Moods 
A beautiful piece of Americana that's defined by it's rough passion and original roots rock sound 




Thoughts 
bluesy folk rock with a country twang. For years I only knew the guy for his earlier instrumental work but I'm happy I checked this later entry out. I took the description in the 'sounds like' description from Wikipedia as it's accurate but bizarre to read, almost clinical in its description. The draw here is the passionate and earthy grittiness found in timeless music of the era. The combination of those sounds produces something distinct and broadly appealing, it's original music that only the American landscape is capable of producing.

﻿Sounds like? 
instrumental melodic post rock - duo or trio playing simple music of tight compositions, sentimental and melodic 






Moods 
It's like an extended instrumental emo jam, an accessible entry into post-rock 






Thoughts 
enjoyable if you like that sound, reminds me of something else I can't quite put my finger on (know that's not helpful, it's the sentimental side of the sound). Accessible as a bridge record for those starting into post rock given the quick melodies and agile drumming. Guitar lines are almost robot like in their sequences, simple scales that give a familiar and immediate sound. 


Is it the kind of record you need to hear before you die? Not at all but it's got some memorable tracks that would work well on mood playlists.
